1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:07,659
Historical specimen records look quiet, but one bad reconciliation can corrupt biodiversity data for years.

2
00:00:07,659 --> 00:00:12,908
Specimen Casebook is an auditable evidence-reconciliation workspace for natural history collections.

3
00:00:12,908 --> 00:00:17,681
It is built around one rule: conflict preserved, science protected.

4
00:00:18,681 --> 00:00:23,630
A specimen label and a field ledger both point to nineteen oh seven.

5
00:00:23,630 --> 00:00:26,294
A legacy database says nineteen oh nine.

6
00:00:26,294 --> 00:00:31,243
If that database is copied forward, a transcription error becomes a published fact.

7
00:00:31,243 --> 00:00:34,289
The problem is not that digitization is slow.

8
00:00:34,289 --> 00:00:37,334
The problem is that uncertainty disappears during digitization.

9
00:00:38,334 --> 00:00:41,835
Our user is a herbarium collections data manager.

10
00:00:41,835 --> 00:00:47,524
They compare labels, field ledgers, old database rows, collector notebooks, and taxonomy histories.

11
00:00:47,524 --> 00:00:51,900
Today that work is manual, fragmented, and difficult to audit.

12
00:00:51,900 --> 00:01:00,214
Their need is simple: reconcile each field, preserve every disagreement, and show exactly where every proposed value came from.

13
00:01:01,214 --> 00:01:03,331
Here is the working prototype.

14
00:01:03,331 --> 00:01:09,681
Claude reads each source, extracts field-level claims with citations, and compares them field by field.

15
00:01:09,681 --> 00:01:14,760
The record summary separates confirmed values from inferred, conflicting, and missing evidence.

16
00:01:14,760 --> 00:01:24,496
The manager can inspect every source, open the conflict queue, review the provisional timeline, and prepare a Darwin Core export without losing provenance.

17
00:01:25,496 --> 00:01:27,528
This is the core demo.

18
00:01:27,528 --> 00:01:31,186
The specimen label says June seventeenth, nineteen oh seven.

19
00:01:31,186 --> 00:01:34,844
The field ledger says June nineteenth, nineteen oh seven.

20
00:01:34,844 --> 00:01:38,502
The legacy database says June seventeenth, nineteen oh nine.

21
00:01:38,502 --> 00:01:42,160
Specimen Casebook does not pick the most convenient answer.

22
00:01:42,160 --> 00:01:51,509
It marks the collection date as conflicting, keeps all three claims attached to their sources, and recommends: do not publish without human review.

23
00:01:51,509 --> 00:01:55,573
Without this safeguard, nineteen oh nine could ship as fact.

24
00:01:55,573 --> 00:01:58,825
With it, the disagreement remains visible and reviewable.

25
00:01:59,825 --> 00:02:03,531
The architecture separates language-model reasoning from publication policy.

26
00:02:03,531 --> 00:02:06,774
Claude converts unstructured evidence into cited claims.

27
00:02:06,774 --> 00:02:09,554
The reconciliation layer compares those claims.

28
00:02:09,554 --> 00:02:13,260
A human resolves only what the evidence supports.

29
00:02:13,260 --> 00:02:18,356
Finally, the approved record exports to Darwin Core with provenance attached.

30
00:02:18,356 --> 00:02:22,525
Claude proposes; the policy layer decides what can ship.

31
00:02:23,525 --> 00:02:26,121
We evaluate restraint, not just extraction.

32
00:02:26,121 --> 00:02:33,476
Our key metric is unsupported resolution rate: the share of conflicts collapsed into one answer without evidence.

33
00:02:33,476 --> 00:02:35,639
The target is zero percent.

34
00:02:35,639 --> 00:02:41,696
We also measure conflict detection, field-to-source accuracy, review triage, and time saved per specimen.

35
00:02:42,696 --> 00:02:48,805
Specimen Casebook turns scattered historical evidence into trustworthy biodiversity records without silent certainty.

36
00:02:48,805 --> 00:02:54,445
It is working software for the collections data managers science depends on.

37
00:02:54,445 --> 00:02:57,734
Explore the live demo and source code.

38
00:02:57,734 --> 00:02:58,674
Conflict preserved.

39
00:02:58,674 --> 00:02:59,614
Science protected.
